Robert Sartin wrote:
&gt; Why is 
&gt; reporting more
&gt; than one such assertion failure not more useful than only 
&gt; reporting the
&gt; first? How is reporting two assertion failures different from a test
&gt; that manages to pack multiple booleans into a single assertTrue and
&gt; pass back the extra failure information in the message?

The main problem I have with continuing after a failure is that you may get
multiple chained failures.

Here is a simple example, for retrieving a value from a Map:

public void testRetrieve() {
    // there&#39;s already a declared Map instance called test.
    assertNull(test.get(&quot;TestKey&quot;));
    test.put(&quot;TestKey&quot;, &quot;This is a test value&quot;);
    Object retrievedValue = test.get(&quot;TestKey&quot;));
    assertNull(retrievedValue);
    assert(retrievedValue instanceof String);
    assertEquals(&quot;This is a test value&quot;, retrievedValue);
}

If the Map was broken (say, it always returned a value for &quot;TestKey&quot;),
there&#39;s no point continuing with the rest of the test.

Obtaining multiple information on failures is already possible in the
framework; simply extract unrelated tests out to seperate test methods.
Pretty much by defintion, if a failure of an assert won&#39;t trigger multiple
other failures, then you&#39;ve got unrelated tests.

